<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911216-0013</DOCNO><DOCID>911216-0013.</DOCID><HL>   Canada Parliament Grants   Banks, Thrifts New Powers</HL><DATE>12/16/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)INSURANCE (INS)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><RE>CANADA (CN)NORTH AMERICA (NME)</RE><LP>   OTTAWA -- The Canadian Parliament approved legislationgranting new powers to banks and other financialinstitutions.   The legislation allows banks to buy insurance companiesand trust companies, which are similar to U.S. savings andloan institutions. Banks will also be allowed to providevarious investment banking services. They have been permittedto own securities dealers since 1987.</LP><TEXT>   Despite intense bank lobbying, the legislators rejectedbank requests for permission to market insurance throughtheir branches and to engage in auto leasing.   The legislation relaxes restrictions on the lendingactivities of trust companies, allowing them to compete moredirectly with banks. Trust companies also will be allowed toown insurance companies.   The legislation is to take effect in the spring, agovernment spokesman said.</TEXT></DOC>